        q3: [],
        option: [`Acromegaly`, `Cushing disease`, ` Hyperthyroidism`,`Infertility`,`Neurologic dysfunction`],
        optionFeedback: [`Acromegaly is caused by growth hormone-producing (somatotroph) adenomas. Growth hormone causes excessive growth of the bones and diabetes but not amenorrhea.`,`Cushing disease is caused by an adrenocorticotropin (ACTH)-producing (corticotroph) adenoma and presents with manifestations of excessive corticosteroid production including weight gain, striae, muscle weakness, hypertension and easy bruising.`,`Hyperthyroidism is caused by a TSH-producing (thyrotroph) adenoma and presents with signs and symptoms of hyperthyroidism such as fatigue, heart palpitations, frequent bowel movements and heat intolerance.`,`The clinical features and radiologic findings are diagnostic of a prolactin-secreting (lactotroph) anterior pituitary adenoma, the most common type of pituitary adenoma. Infertility in both men and women is a frequent complication of excess prolactin. `,`Neurologic dysfunction is most often seen with nonfunctioning pituitary adenomas, which are not diagnosed early (since they lack signs of hormone overproduction) and may grow to large size, causing mass effects. `],
