        option: [`Elevated serum cortisol despite high-dose dexamethasone dose`, `Inability of oral glucose load to suppress growth hormone levels`,`Hyperprolactinemia`,`Increased serum thyroid stimulating hormone (TSH) level`,`Increased urine catecholamine levels`],
        optionFeedback: [`Dexamethasone suppression tests measure the response of the adrenal glands to ACTH.  This patient does not show signs or symptoms of Cushing syndrome.`,`The physical findings suggest an excess of growth hormone and the laboratory evidence of diabetes is consistent with a growth hormone-producing (somatotroph) pituitary adenoma since growth hormone induces peripheral insulin resistance. In unaffected individuals, growth hormone production is suppressed by insulin produced in response to an oral glucose load (an example of feedback regulation), but adenomas are autonomous and do not respond to normal regulatory signals. `,`Excessive prolactin secretion is seen with prolactin-producing (lactotroph) adenoma, which presents with galactorrhea and amenorrhea in women and infertility in men and women.`,`Increased serum TSH is seen with TSH-producing (thyrotroph) adenoma, which presents with signs and symptoms of hyperthyroidism.`,`Increased urine catecholamines are seen with pheochromocytoma, a tumor of the adrenal medulla and other neuroendocrine glands.  Patients have hypertension; about two thirds of them have paroxysmal episodes of hypertension. They do not have diabetes.`],
        optionStyleType: `st-lower-alpha`,
