        ansText: `Rationale:- The physical findings suggest an excess of growth hormone and the laboratory evidence of diabetes is consistent with a growth hormone-producing (somatotroph) pituitary adenoma since growth hormone induces peripheral insulin resistance. In unaffected individuals, growth hormone production is suppressed by insulin produced in response to an oral glucose load (an example of feedback regulation), but adenomas are autonomous and do not respond to normal regulatory signals.   `,
