        q: `A 69-year-old man has become progressively obtunded over the past week. He has an 80 pack-year smoking history. On physical examination, he is afebrile and normotensive. A head CT scan shows no intracerebral hemorrhages. Laboratory findings include serum Na<sup>+</sup>, 115 mmol/L (136â€“145 mmol/L); K<sup>+</sup>, 4.2 mmol/L (3.5â€“5.0 mmol/L); Clâ€“, 85 mmol/L (95â€“105 mmol/L); bicarbonate, 23 mmol/L (22â€“28 mmol/L); serum glucose, 80 mg/dL (fasting, 70â€“110 mg/dL); blood urea nitrogen, 19 mg/dL (0.1â€“1.0 mg/dL); and creatinine, 1.7 mg/dL (0.6â€“1.2 mg/dL). Which of the following neoplasms is most likely to be present in this man?`,
