        optionFeedback: [`Anterior pituitary adenoma would not secrete ADH, which is a posterior pituitary hormone.`,`Adrenal tumors do not produce ADH.`,`Pheochromocytoma produces catecholamines, not ADH.`,`The clinical history of neurologic dysfunction and the laboratory finding of hyponatremia are suggestive of the syndrome of inappropriate ADH secretion. This is often seen in small cell lung cancer, when the tumor cells secrete the hormone (an example of a paraneoplastic syndrome). The history of smoking is consistent with lung cancer. `,`Paraneoplastic syndromes associated with excessive hormone secretion occur with renal cell carcinoma but are usually caused by inappropriate secretion of erythropoietin leading to polycythemia, not release of ADH leading to electrolyte abnormalities. `],
