        optionFeedback: [`Thyrotrophs as a cause of hypothyroidism, perhaps in the setting of an anterior pituitary lesion, would show reduced TSH.    In a thyrotroph adenoma, the patient would have increased TSH.`,`Hypothalamic dysfunction as a cause of hypothyroidism would show reduced TSH.`,`Somatotroph abnormalities would not affect thyroid hormones.`,`Thyroid C cells are neuroendocrine cells that produce calcitonin, not thyroid hormone.`,`The clinical features suggest primary hypothyroidism, and the laboratory findings of reduced T<sub>4</sub> and increased TSH are diagnostic. Primary hypothyroidism may be caused by autoimmune thyroid disease (Hashimoto thyroiditis) or dietary iodine deficiency, or it may be iatrogenic (post-surgery for cancer). Whatever the underlying cause, the thyroid follicular cells are not functioning adequately. `],
