        optionFeedback: [`Thyroxine (T<sub>4</sub>) levels are increased, not decreased, due to overproduction from the overstimulated thyroid follicular epithelial cells.`,`Exophthalmos and diffuse thyroid enlargement are typical for Graves disease, an autoimmune disease in which antibodies against the TSH receptor on thyroid follicular cells mimic the action of TSH and stimulate the cells to produce excessive amounts of thyroid hormones. TSH levels are reduced because the increased production of thyroid hormones (T<sub>4</sub> and T<sub>3</sub>) causes feedback inhibition of TSH.   The concordance rate of Graves disease in identical twins is 50%, suggesting a genetic component in the pathogenesis of this disease. `,`Antithyroglobulin antibodies are found in patients with Hashimoto thyroiditis. `,`Increased levels of TRH are seen in those with thyrotroph pituitary adenoma.`,`Triiodothyronine (T<sub>3</sub>) levels are increased, not decreased, because of overproduction from the overstimulated thyroid follicular epithelial cells.`],
